04553nmm a2200853Ia 9780520918276DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209182767 a10.1525/97805209182762doi  a(DE-B1597)570380  a(OCoLC)1202625742  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aGV251b.T64 1997eb 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a613.7/09432201 aToepfer, Karl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpire of Ecstasy :bNudity and Movement in German Body Culture, 1910–1935 /cKarl Toepfer.  aReprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (439 p.) :b1 frontisp.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWeimar and Now: German Cultural Criticism ;v130 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmpire of Ecstasy offers a novel interpretation of the explosion of German body culture between the two wars—nudism and nude dancing, gymnastics and dance training, dance photography and criticism, and diverse genres of performance from solo dancing to mass movement choirs. Karl Toepfer presents this dynamic subject as a vital and historically unique construction of "modern identity." The modern body, radiating freedom and power, appeared to Weimar artists and intelligentsia to be the source of a transgressive energy, as well as the sign and manifestation of powerful, mysterious "inner" conditions. Toepfer shows how this view of the modern body sought to extend the aesthetic experience beyond the boundaries imposed by rationalized life and to transcend these limits in search of ecstasy. With the help of much unpublished or long-forgotten archival material (including many little-known photographs), he investigates the process of constructing an "empire" of appropriative impulses toward ecstasy. Toepfer presents the work of such well-known figures as Rudolf Laban, Mary Wigman, and Oskar Schlemmer, along with less-known but equally fascinating body culture practitioners. His book is certain to become required reading for historians of dance, body culture, and modernism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aBody imagexGermany. 0aBody imagezGermany. 0aDancexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aDancexHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aDancezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNudismxSociological aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudismxSociological aspectsxHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudismzGermanyxSociological aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aNudity in dancexHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudity in dancexHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aNudity in dancezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhysical education and trainingxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aPhysical education and trainingxHistoryy20th centuryxGermany. 0aPhysical education and trainingzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 4aEuropean history. 4aarchitecture. 4aculture. 4aempire. 4afilm. 4afreedom. 4ahistory of architecture. 4ahistory of art. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4aliberty. 4aphilosophy. 4apolitical philosophy. 4asocial philosophy. 4athe arts. 4awars. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918276?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918276423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918276/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles